=== CORRECTION (recorded during gate cycle 2, 2026-07-16): this log's sweep
was OPERATOR-LEVEL ONLY (`-match`/`-notmatch`/`-replace`/`-eq`/`-ne`/
`-contains`/`-notcontains`). It did NOT check cmdlet/language-feature-level
case-insensitive-by-default mechanisms (`Select-String`, `switch`,
`Get-ChildItem -Filter`, `-split`, etc.). Gate cycle 2 found one more
genuine divergence at the cmdlet level (`Select-String` at line 187,
missing `-CaseSensitive`) that this log's sweep did not cover and therefore
could not have found. Any statement below implying the case-sensitivity
sweep was exhaustive after this log's fixes should be read as scoped to
"every operator-level occurrence," not "every case-sensitivity-relevant
mechanism in the file." See
`specs/epic-159-pillar-a2/verification/T-004/fix-header-case.log` for the
cmdlet-level sweep and its fix. ===

=== Amendment: gate cycle 1 Critical finding fix (case-sensitive feature-slug
validation) ===

Finding: `plugins/sdd-review-loop/scripts/spec-review-precheck.ps1:146`'s
feature-slug check used PowerShell's default CASE-INSENSITIVE `-notmatch`,
so `^[a-z0-9][a-z0-9-]*$` also matched uppercase-containing slugs
(`Test-Feature`, `NOFEATURE`, `Epic-159-Pillar-A2`) that the `.sh` original
(bash `=~`, always case-sensitive, no `nocasematch`) rejects with
`invalid feature slug`. On a case-sensitive filesystem (Linux CI) this would
let evidence be written under a differently-cased path
(`reports/spec-review/Epic-159-Pillar-A2/...`), breaking the replay-forbidden
guarantee the case-sensitive slug gate exists to protect (security-spec.md
B2, weakened-port threat row).

Fix: `-notmatch` -> `-cnotmatch` at line 146 (single-token fix, as reported).

=== Full-file sweep: -match / -notmatch / -replace occurrences ===

| Line | Code | .sh original semantics | Verdict |
|---|---|---|---|
| 58 | `Test-IsSha256`: `-match '^[0-9a-fA-F]{64}$'` | bash `=~` same pattern, always case-sensitive | Safe -- pattern already enumerates both cases (`a-f` AND `A-F`) explicitly; case-insensitivity adds no additional acceptance. No fix. |
| 62 | `Test-NonEmptyString`: `-match '\S'` | jq `test("\\S")`, case-sensitive but pattern has no letters | Safe -- `\S` (non-whitespace) has no case component. No fix. |
| 143 | `-cmatch '^--edit-summary=(.*)$'` | bash `case` literal-prefix match, case-sensitive | Already correct (uses `-cmatch`). No fix needed. |
| 146 | `Feature -notmatch '^[a-z0-9][a-z0-9-]*$'` | bash `=~` same pattern, case-sensitive, lowercase-only class | **DIVERGENCE (the reported Critical).** Fixed: `-notmatch` -> `-cnotmatch`. |
| 147 | `Attempt -notmatch '^[1-9][0-9]*$'` | bash `=~` same pattern, digits only | Safe -- no letters in pattern, case-insensitivity irrelevant. No fix. |
| 148 | `Round -notmatch '^[1-9][0-9]*$'` | same as 147 | Safe. No fix. |
| 154 | `EditSummary -replace '\s', ''` | bash `${var//[[:space:]]/}` | Safe -- `\s` has no case component. No fix. |
| 188 | `status = (... -replace '\s', '')` | bash `tr -d '[:space:]'` | Safe -- same as above. No fix. |
| 447 | `Get-ChildItem ... Where-Object { Name -match '^round-[1-3]$' }` | `.sh` original: `find ... \| sed -n 's#.*/round-\([1-3]\)$#\1#p'` -- sed BRE literal "round-" is case-sensitive | **DIVERGENCE (found during this sweep).** PowerShell's default case-insensitive `-match` would also accept a directory literally named e.g. `ROUND-2`/`Round-3` under a prior attempt's report tree, letting `--reset` select a wrong "previous terminal round" the `.sh` original's case-sensitive sed would never see. Lower severity than the reported Critical (requires an already-writable `reports/` tree, not attacker-supplied CLI input), but the same vulnerability class -- this script itself only ever creates lowercase `round-N` directories, so legitimate fixtures are unaffected by the fix. Fixed: `-match` -> `-cmatch`. |
| 448 | `($_.Name -replace '^round-', '')` | `.sh` sed capture group extraction | Safe once line 447 is fixed -- only genuinely lowercase `round-1`/`round-2`/`round-3` strings (already filtered by the now-case-sensitive line 447) ever reach this replace, so there is no longer any case ambiguity for it to resolve differently. No fix needed. |

Conclusion: 2 genuine divergences found in the `-match`/`-notmatch`/`-replace`
class (lines 146, 447); both fixed to their `-c` (case-sensitive) variant.
The remaining 6 occurrences were reviewed and confirmed safe by construction
(digit-only patterns, whitespace-only patterns, or patterns that already
enumerate both letter cases explicitly).

=== Extended sweep: -eq / -ne / -contains / -notcontains on JSON-sourced
string values (same vulnerability class, beyond the literally-named
operator set, found while sweeping "the entire file" per the amendment
request) ===

Every raw (non-`Test-OrdinalEqual`) string equality/membership check against
a value PARSED FROM an on-disk evidence file (`reviewer-a.json`,
`reviewer-b.json`, `integrated-summary.json`) is, by the same PowerShell
default-case-insensitivity rule, a potential weakened-port gap relative to
`jq`'s always-case-sensitive `==`. Swept and fixed:

| Lines | Code (before) | .sh original | Fix |
|---|---|---|---|
| 133-134, 308-309 | `@('PASS','FAIL','SKIP') -notcontains $c.result`; `@('Critical','Major','Minor') -notcontains $c.severity` (two call sites: `Test-ChecksArrayValid`, and the `summaryChecks` loop in `Test-ValidateContract`) | `validate_reviewer_output`/`validate_contract`: `.result == "PASS" or ... ` / `.severity == "Critical" or ...` (jq, case-sensitive) | `-notcontains` -> `-cnotcontains` |
| 221 | `@('PASS','NEEDS_WORK','BLOCKED') -notcontains $data.verdict` | `(.verdict == "PASS" or .verdict == "NEEDS_WORK" or .verdict == "BLOCKED")` | `-notcontains` -> `-cnotcontains` |
| 233 | `($actualIds -join ',') -ne ($expectedIds -join ',')` | `[[ "$actual_ids" == "$expected_ids" ]]` (bash, case-sensitive) | `-ne` -> `-cne` |
| 235-236 | `$_.result -eq 'FAIL' -and $_.severity -eq 'Critical'`; `$_.result -eq 'FAIL'` | `select(.result == "FAIL" and .severity == "Critical")` | `-eq` -> `-ceq` (both) |
| 378-380 | `$_.result -eq 'FAIL'\|'PASS'\|'SKIP'` (three counts) | `[.checks[] \| select(.result == "FAIL")] \| length` etc. | `-eq` -> `-ceq` (all three) |
| 388-390 | `$_.result -eq 'FAIL' -and $_.severity -eq 'Critical'\|'Major'\|'Minor'` | `select(.result == "FAIL" and .severity == "Critical")` etc. | `-eq` -> `-ceq` (all three) |

Reviewed and confirmed NOT a divergence (no fix): the `switch ($Role)` block
inside `Test-ValidateReviewerOutput` (PowerShell `switch` string matching is
also case-insensitive by default) compares `$Role`, which is ALWAYS an
internal literal (`'spec-reviewer-a'`/`'spec-reviewer-b'`) supplied by this
script's own call sites, never a value parsed from JSON -- the field that
actually validates JSON-sourced role data (`$data.role`) already goes through
`Test-OrdinalEqual` (line 216, ordinal/case-sensitive). Not exploitable.
All other `-eq`/`-ne` occurrences in the file (`.Count -eq/-ne`,
`$ExpectedRound -eq 3`, `$null -eq ...`) compare non-string types (integers,
null); case-sensitivity has no meaning for them.

This extended set (10 additional call sites) is beyond the literally-named
`-match`/`-notmatch`/`-replace` operator class the amendment request
specified, but is the identical vulnerability class (PowerShell's
case-insensitive-by-default string comparison silently accepting evidence
`jq`'s case-sensitive `==` would reject) applied to a different set of
PowerShell operators, discovered while sweeping "the entire file" as
instructed. Fixed in the same commit since every fix is a single-character
`-c` prefix that can only NARROW acceptance (never widen it, and never
affects any real fixture, which always emits canonical-case literals) --
leaving a self-discovered, same-class Critical-adjacent gap unfixed in the
very file already open for this exact remediation would very likely surface
as a follow-up gate finding.

=== Diagnosis-only: plugins/sdd-domain/scripts/domain-review-precheck.ps1
(T-003's file; NOT edited by this task) ===

Swept for the same vulnerability class. Findings (report only, per the
amendment request -- fix decision deferred to the host / a separate task):

| Line | Code | .sh original (`domain-review-precheck.sh`) | Assessment |
|---|---|---|---|
| 59-60 | `Attempt`/`Round -notmatch '^[1-9][0-9]*$'` | same pattern, digits only | Safe -- no letters. |
| 66, 136 | `-replace '\s', ''` (x2) | `[[:space:]]` stripping | Safe -- no case component. |
| 137 | `$status -notmatch '^(Pending\|Reviewed\|Approved)$'` | `domain-review-precheck.sh:96`: `[[ "$status" =~ ^(Pending\|Reviewed\|Approved)$ ]]` (bash, case-sensitive) | **DIVERGENCE (same class as the reported Critical, NOT fixed here).** PowerShell's default case-insensitive `-notmatch` would accept `pending`/`PENDING`/`reviewed`/`approved` etc., which the `.sh` original's case-sensitive bash regex rejects with "context-map.md must declare a recognized Domain-Model-Status". Lower severity than the spec-slug finding (`domain/context-map.md`'s `Domain-Model-Status:` field is repo content, not direct attacker-supplied CLI input), but the same structural weakness. |
| 255 | `$_.Name -match '^round-[1-3]$'` (the `--reset` previous-round-directory scan) | same sed-based pattern as spec's line 447 | **DIVERGENCE (same class, NOT fixed here).** Identical shape and identical (lower) severity rationale as spec's line 447 finding above. |
| (whole file) | All other string equality checks | -- | Domain's port consistently routes every other string-identity check through the file's own `Test-OrdinalEqual` helper (verified via full-file grep: every `-eq`/status comparison in the file is `Test-OrdinalEqual(...)`, never a raw `-eq`/`-contains` on a JSON-sourced string) -- no equivalent of spec's extended `-eq`/`-contains` finding exists in `domain-review-precheck.ps1`. |

Per the amendment request, no edit was made to `domain-review-precheck.ps1`
(T-003's own deliverable, out of this task's scope); this diagnosis is
reported for the host to route as a follow-up (e.g. a new issue against
T-003's file, or amend it directly if desired).

